'''''Kahaani''''' ({{IPA-hns|k<U+0259><U+02C8><U+0266>a<U+02D0>ni|IPA}}; "Story") is a 2012 [[Bollywood|Indian]] [[thriller (genre)|thriller]] film directed and co-produced by [[Sujoy Ghosh]]. It stars [[Vidya Balan]] as Vidya Bagchi, a pregnant woman searching for her missing husband in [[Kolkata]] during the festival of [[Durga Puja]], assisted by Satyaki "Rana" Sinha ([[Parambrata Chatterjee]]) and Khan ([[Nawazuddin Siddiqui]]).

Made on a "shoestring budget" of {{INRConvert|80|m}},<ref>{{cite web|url= http://ibnlive.in.com/news/vidya-balans-kahaani-declared-a-hit/238407-8-66.html|title=Vidya Balan's ''Kahaani'' declared a hit|publisher=[[CNN-IBN]]|date=12 March 2012|accessdate=21 March 2013|agency=[[Indo-Asian News Service]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-01-10/news-interviews/36257559_1_kahaani-sujoy-ghosh-amitabh-bachchan | title=Sujoy Ghosh keen to cast Amitabh Bachchan in ''Kahaani 2''|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|date=10 January 2013|accessdate=21 March 2013|agency=Indo-Asian News Service}}</ref> ''Kahaani'' was conceived and developed by Ghosh, who co-wrote the film with Advaita Kala. Shot in Kolkata, the crew often employed [[guerrilla filmmaking|guerrilla-filmmaking]] techniques on the city's streets to avoid attracting attention. The film was noted for its deft portrayal of the city and for making use of many local crew and cast members. ''Kahaani'' explores themes of feminism and motherhood in male-dominated Indian society. The film also makes several allusions to [[Satyajit Ray]]'s films such as ''[[Charulata]]'' (1964) and ''[[Aranyer Dinratri]]'' (1970).

''Kahaani'' was released worldwide on 9 March 2012. Critics praised the screenplay, the cinematography and the performances of the lead actors. Due to critical acclaim and word-of-mouth publicity, the film became a [[sleeper hit]], earning {{INRConvert|1.04|b}} worldwide in 50 days. At the end of its theatrical run the film won several awards, including three [[National Film Awards]] and five [[Filmfare Awards]]. The latter included trophies for [[Filmfare Award for Best Director|Best Director]] (Ghosh) and [[Filmfare Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] (Balan).

==Plot==
<!-- Per WP:FilmPlot, plot summaries for feature film articles should be between 400 and 700 words. Please do not expand it. Thanks -->
The film opens with a poison-gas attack on a [[Kolkata Metro|Kolkata Metro Rail]] compartment, killing the passengers on board. Two years later Vidya Bagchi ([[Vidya Balan]]), a pregnant [[software engineer]], arrives in [[Kolkata]] from London during the [[Durga Puja]] festivities in search of her missing husband, Arnab Bagchi. A police officer, Satyaki "Rana" Sinha ([[Parambrata Chatterjee]]), offers to help. Although Vidya claims that Arnab went to Kolkata on an assignment for the National Data Center (NDC), initial investigations suggest that no such person was employed by the NDC.

Agnes D'mello, the NDC's head of human resources, suggests to Vidya that her husband resembled former employee Milan Damji ([[Indraneil Sengupta]]), whose file is probably kept in the old NDC office. Before Agnes can provide any further help she is killed by Bob Biswas ([[Saswata Chatterjee]]), an assassin working undercover as a life insurance agent. Vidya and Rana break into the NDC office and find Damji's file, barely escaping an encounter with Bob, who is searching for the same information. Meanwhile, the attempts to obtain Damji's records have attracted the attention of two [[Intelligence Bureau (India)|Intelligence Bureau]] (IB) officials in Delhi&nbsp;<U+2013> the chief Bhaskaran K. ([[Dhritiman Chatterjee]]) and his deputy Khan ([[Nawazuddin Siddiqui]]). Khan arrives in Kolkata and reveals that Damji was a rogue IB agent responsible for the poison-gas attack. In spite of Khan's warnings, Vidya continues her search, fearing that Arnab's resemblance to Damji may have led him into trouble.

The address on Damji's record leads Vidya and Rana to a dilapidated flat. An errand boy from the neighbourhood tea stall identifies R. Sridhar, an NDC officer, as a frequent visitor to Damji's flat. Bob attempts to kill Vidya, but fails, and is run over by a [[Tempo (car)|Tempo]] during a chase. Examination of Bob's mobile phone leads Vidya and Rana to an [[IP address]] sending instructions to kill her. They break into Sridhar's office to verify his IP address, but he is alerted electronically and returns to his office. Vidya accidentally shoots Sridhar dead during a scuffle, which upsets Khan, who had wanted him alive.

Sridhar's computer data reveals a code, which when deciphered reveals Bhaskaran's phone number. Vidya calls Bhaskaran to tell him that she has retrieved sensitive documents from Sridhar's office. She asks Bhaskaran to help find her husband in exchange for the documents, but Bhaskaran tells her to contact the local police. Vidya soon gets a call from an unknown number however, warning her that she should hand over the documents to the caller if she wishes to see her husband alive. Khan thinks the caller is Milan Damji.

Vidya goes to meet Damji, followed by Rana and Khan. Damji cuts the meeting short when Vidya expresses her doubt that he will be able to return her husband in exchange for the sensitive file, and he attempts to leave. Vidya tries to stop him, and in the ensuing struggle Damji draws a gun on her. Vidya disarms him using the prosthetic belly she has been using to fake her pregnancy, before shooting him with his own gun. She flees into the crowd before the police arrive, leaving a thank-you note for Rana and a [[USB flash drive|pen drive]] containing data from Sridhar's computer, which leads to Bhaskaran's arrest. Rana concludes that no Vidya or Arnab Bagchi ever existed, and that Vidya had been using the police and the IB to achieve her own ends.

Vidya is revealed to be the widow of Arup Basu ([[Abir Chatterjee]]), an IB officer and Damji's colleague, who was killed in the poison-gas attack. In her mission to avenge his death, Vidya was helped by retired IB officer Pratap Bajpayee ([[Darshan Jariwala]]), who suspected the involvement of a top IB official.

==Cast==
* [[Vidya Balan]] as Vidya Bagchi
* [[Parambrata Chatterjee]] as Satyaki "Rana" Sinha
* [[Nawazuddin Siddiqui]] as Khan
* [[Indraneil Sengupta]] as Milan Damji
* [[Dhritiman Chatterjee]] as Bhaskaran K.
* [[Saswata Chatterjee]] as Bob Biswas
* [[Darshan Jariwala]] as Colonel Pratap Bajpayee
* [[Abir Chatterjee]] as Arup Basu
* Shantilal Mukherjee as R. Shridhar
* [[Kharaj Mukherjee]] as Inspector Chatterjee, a friendly inspector at the Kalighat Police Station.
* Colleen Blanche as Agnes D'mello
* Nitya Ganguli as Mr. Das, the guest house owner.
* Ritabrata Mukherjee as Bishnu, a worker at the guest house.
* Pamela Bhuttoria as Sapna, an employee at NDC.
* Kalyan Chatterjee as Paresh Pal, a clay artist and a police informer.
* [[Riddhi Sen]] as Poltu, a worker at a tea-stall.

==Production==

===Development===
[[Sujoy Ghosh]] approached novelist and script-writer Advaita Kala with the idea for the film.<ref name=Kala@ZN>{{cite news
|url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/movies/vidya-balan-is-the-hero-of-kahaani-says-scriptwriter-advaita-kala_75637.htm
|title=Vidya Balan is the hero of ''Kahaani'', says scriptwriter Advaita Kala
|publisher=[[Zee News]]
|agency=[[Press Trust of India]] (PTI)
|accessdate=30 March 2012
|date=16 November 2010
}}</ref> Kala took inspiration from her experience in Kolkata, where she had followed her boyfriend in 1999, akin to the protagonist in the film.<ref name="mitra toi 3-16">{{cite news
|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-16/books/31142700_1_kahaani-sujoy-ghosh-vidya-balan
|title=Vidya's journey was my own: Advaita Kala
|first=Ipshita
|last=Mitra
|newspaper=The Times of India
|accessdate=8 May 2012
|date=16 March 2012
}}</ref> She reported that despite facing a language barrier and the chaos and poverty of the metropolis, she was charmed by the warmth of the people, which was reflected in the film.<ref name="real life znews">{{cite news
|url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/movies/kahaani-story-inspired-from-real-life-experiences_107223.htm
|title=''Kahaani'' story inspired from real-life experiences
|publisher=Zee News
|agency=PTI
|accessdate=21 March 2012
|date=7 March 2012
}}</ref> Kala started writing in 2009 and finished the 185-page script by February 2010.<ref name="dasgupta toi 1152012">{{cite news
|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-01-15/news-interviews/30627829_1_novel-sujoy-ghosh-release
|title=Vidya's ''Kahaani'' to release as novel
|first=Priyanka
|last=Dasgupta
|newspaper=The Times of India
|agency=[[Times News Network]] (TNN)
|accessdate=26 March 2012
|date=15 January 2012
}}</ref><ref>{{cite web
|url= http://ibnlive.in.com/news/advaita-kala-had-to-tell-vidyas-story-right/237060-40-103.html
|title=''Kahaani'': Advaita Kala says she had to tell Vidya's story right
|first=Malvika
|last=Bhardwaj
|publisher=[[CNN-IBN]]
|accessdate=21 March 2012
|date=7 March 2012
}}</ref> Her research included reading the books ''Open Secrets: India's Intelligence Unveiled'' by Maloy Krishna Dhar and ''India's External Intelligence: Secrets of [[Research and Analysis Wing]] (RAW)'' by V. K. Singh.<ref name="mitra toi 3-16"/>

Ghosh, who co-wrote the story and the screenplay, began to plan the film while awaiting the release of his previous film ''[[Aladin (2009 film)|Aladin]]'' (2009), but the dismal response to ''Aladin'' was a setback. He had to approach several producers to finance him for ''Kahaani'', but was refused<ref name="abp 7 april ghosh"/> and discouraged from making the film owing to three factors: a pregnant woman as the lead star, a bunch of unknown Bengali actors as the supporting cast and Kolkata as a backdrop.<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/bollywood/kahaani-everything-that-a-film-should-not-be-sujoy-ghosh_109182.htm
|title=''Kahaani'' everything that a film should not be: Sujoy Ghosh
|publisher=Zee News
|agency=PTI
|accessdate=10 April 2012
|date=9 April 2012
}}</ref> [[Yashraj Films]] were willing to produce the film, but wanted Ghosh to sign a three-film deal, which he declined because he did not want that much commitment.<ref name="abp 7 april ghosh"/>

Bengali film actor [[Prosenjit Chatterjee]] encouraged Ghosh to shoot in Kolkata.<ref name="KahaaniOfKahaani">{{cite news
|url=http://newindianexpress.com/entertainment/hindi/article324563.ece
|title=The story behind ''Kahaani''
|first=Ayaz
|last=Shaikh
|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]
|accessdate=26 March 2012
|date=26 February 2012
}}</ref> Ghosh finally selected Kolkata for several reasons: the director's acquaintance with the city, its mix of modernity and old-world charm,<ref name="KahaaniOfKahaani"/> and budget constraints. Kolkata is a cheaper location than Mumbai or Delhi, where most Bollywood films are shot.<ref name="moneycontrol ghosh iv">{{cite news
|url=http://www.moneycontrol.com/news/entertainment/if-kahaani-failed-id-have-to-pack-my-baggo-sujoy-ghosh_689018.html
|title=If ''Kahaani'' failed I'd have to pack my bag & go: Sujoy Ghosh
|publisher=Moneycontrol
|agency=CNBC-TV18
|accessdate=5 April 2012
|date=4 April 2012
}}</ref>

Ghosh admitted in an interview that after his two preceding directorial ventures&nbsp;<U+2013> ''Aladin'' and ''[[Home Delivery (film)|Home Delivery]]'' (2005)&nbsp;<U+2013> performed miserably at the box office, ''Kahaani'' was his last chance to create a niche as a director.<ref name="ibn ghosh interview flop">{{cite video
|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eaNZSI4zX2o&feature=related
|title=Rajeev Masand interview with director Sujoy Ghosh on ''Kahaani''
|publisher=CNN-IBN
|people=Ghosh, Sujoy
|type=Television production
|year=2012
|month=March
|time=1:25
|accessdate=30 March 2012
}}</ref> He added that the film's plot twist came somewhat accidentally. Having described the skeleton of the story to a friend during its development, the friend called him back a few days later to enquire about his film. The friend had mistakenly imagined sequences which he assumed to be parts of the plot, from which the twist ending was derived.<ref name="ibn ghosh interview twist">{{cite video
|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eaNZSI4zX2o&feature=related
|title=Rajeev Masand interview with director Sujoy Ghosh on ''Kahaani''
|publisher=CNN-IBN
|people=Ghosh, Sujoy
|type=Television production
|year=2012
|month=March
|time=4:10
|accessdate=30 March 2012
}}</ref>

===Casting===
[[File:Vidya Balan at The DVD launch of 'Kahaani' (3).jpg|thumb|Vidya Balan (on right) was the first choice of director Sujoy Ghosh (on left) for the leading role in the film.| alt= Vidya Balan (on right) and Sujoy Ghosh(on left)]]
Vidya Balan was the first choice of both writer Advaita Kala and director Sujoy Ghosh.<ref name="real life znews"/> Ghosh had planned for a long time to work with Balan and approached her in 2010.<ref name=Ghosh@ZN>{{cite news
|url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/movies/aladdin-flopped-as-i-failed-to-tell-a-story-sujoy-ghosh_105652.htm
|title=''Aladdin'' flopped as I failed to tell a story: Sujoy Ghosh
|publisher=Zee News
|agency=IANS
|accessdate=6 April 2012
|date=10 February 2012
}}</ref> Unimpressed with the plot outline, Balan refused, only changing her mind after having read the completed script.<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/movies/vidya-played-choosy-before-saying-yes-for-kahaani_105993.htm
|title=Vidya played choosy before saying yes for ''Kahaani''
|publisher=Zee News
|agency=IANS
|accessdate=21 March 2012
|date=16 February 2012
}}</ref>

Ghosh chose mostly Bengali actors as he wanted to make the characters as authentic as possible.<ref name="Sujoy on toes @ HT">{{cite news
|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Bollywood/I-wanted-to-be-on-my-toes-Sujoy-Ghosh/Article1-822989.aspx
|title=I wanted to be on my toes: Sujoy Ghosh
|first=Debasmita
|last=Ghosh
|newspaper=Hindustan Times
|accessdate=22 May 2012
|date=9 March 2012
}}</ref><ref name="inside Story @ Hindu">{{cite news
|url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/cinema/article3006073.ece
|title=The inside story
|first=Sangeetha
|last=Dundoo
|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]
|accessdate=22 May 2012
|date=17 March 2012
|location=Chennai, India
}}</ref> The role of the Inspector Satyaki "Rana" Sinha was first offered to [[Chandan Roy Sanyal]], but he could not take the part due to other commitments.<ref name="Team Tolly @ TT" /> Parambrata Chatterjee, a [[Cinema of West Bengal|Bengali actor]] whose acting in the film ''[[The Bong Connection]]'' (2006) had impressed Ghosh at the [[Mumbai Academy of the Moving Image]] festival, was later offered the role in ''Kahaani''.<ref name=Parambrata@Rediff>{{cite web
|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-interview-with-parambrata-chatterjee/20120316.htm
|title=Meet the other hero of ''Kahaani''
|first=Patcy
|last=N
|publisher=[[Rediff]]
|accessdate=16 March 2012
|date=16 March 2012
}}</ref> Chatterjee had earlier worked with Balan in her d<U+00E9>but film ''[[Bhalo Theko]]'' (2003).<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-23/news-interviews/31229680_1_vidya-balan-sujoy-ghosh-film-kahaani
|title=Vidya Balan my best co-star: Parambrata Chatterjee
|newspaper=The Times of India
|agency=PTI
|accessdate=26 March 2012
|date=23 March 2012
}}</ref>

The casting director Roshmi Banerjee suggested Nawazuddin Siddiqui for the role of Khan. Siddiqui, who had only had minor roles in Bollywood up to that time, was surprised that for the first time he would not have to portray a beggar.<ref name="abp 7 april ghosh"/> Saswata Chatterjee, another Bengali actor, was surprised as well when he was offered the role of the contract killer Bob Biswas. He thought there were suitable actors in Hindi film industry for the role.<ref name="pheno 3 ibn">{{cite news
|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/politicians-beware-bob-biswas-says-ek-minute/245154-8-66.html
|title=Bob Biswas: Saswata Chatterjee, the man behind the cult assassin
|first=Rituparna
|last=Chatterjee
|publisher=CNN-IBN
|accessdate=10 April 2012
|date=3 April 2012
}}</ref> He said that Ghosh had known him since childhood and was impressed with his acting, so he wanted him as Bob Biswas.<ref name="toi 30march12chatterjee">{{cite news
|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/news-interviews/Kahaani-is-my-huge-break-Saswata-Chatterjee/articleshow/12455053.cms
|title=''Kahaani'' is my huge break: Saswata Chatterjee
|newspaper=The Times of India
|agency=TNN
|accessdate=30 March 2012
|date=30 March 2012
}}</ref>

Ghosh went against the expectations of casting a popular actor from Bollywood. He signed Bengali actor Abir Chatterjee to play Balan's husband. According to Ghosh, popular Bollywood actors were not willing to work with him after his two previous flops. He also believed that audience might expect more screen-time from a better-known actor.<ref name="Sujoy @ India West">{{cite web
|url=http://indiawest.com/news/3597-sujoy-ghosh-kahaani-could-be-the-story-of-any-mother.html
|title=Sujoy Ghosh: ''Kahaani'' could be the story of any mother
|first=R.M
|last=Vijayakar
|publisher=India West
|accessdate=22 May 2012
|date=19 March 2012
}}</ref> Several other Bengali film and television actors, such as Indraneil Sengupta and Kharaj Mukherjee, were cast in supporting roles.<ref name="Team Tolly @ TT">{{cite news
|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1120316/jsp/entertainment/story_15255285.jsp
|title=The ''Kahaani'' of team tolly
|date=16 March 2012
|newspaper=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]]
|accessdate=26 March 2012
|location=Calcutta, India
}}</ref>

===Characters===
Before the shooting of the film began, Balan started to use a prosthetic belly to look as close to authentically pregnant as possible. According to news reports, she met doctors and pregnant women to learn about the typical lifestyle and nuances of a pregnant woman, and also made lists of rules and superstitions followed by pregnant women.<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/movies/vidya-balan-gets-into-character-of-pregnant-woman-for-kahaani_104909.htm
|title=Vidya Balan gets into character of pregnant woman for ''Kahaani''
|publisher=Zee News
|agency=[[Asian News International]] (ANI)
|accessdate=26 March 2012
|date=30 January 2012
}}</ref> Balan said that during her college days she often used to imitate pregnant ladies during stand-up acting among friends, an experience that helped her during the shooting.<ref name="cakewalk">{{cite web
|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/vidya-balan-the-dirty-picutre-kahaani-paa-heyy-babyy/1/168320.html
|title=Playing pregnant woman was cakewalk for Vidya Balan
|work=India Today
|agency=IANS
|accessdate=24 May 2013
|date=11 January 2012
}}</ref>

While briefing Saswata Chatterjee about his character, the cold-blooded killer Bob Biswas, Ghosh used the phrase ''"Binito Bob"'' (meaning polite Bob), which crystallised the notion of Bob's manners. Further discussions led to the inclusion of paunch and a bald patch. Chatterjee devised the mannerism of rubbing his nails together as some Indians believe doing that helps prevent hair loss. The mannerism was well- noted and praised by the viewers.<ref name="toi 30march12chatterjee"/> Ghosh was surprised at how Bob Biswas was greeted by fans as a cult figure. He emphasised that the deliberate ordinariness of Bob Biswas was portrayed so convincingly by Chatterjee that the viewers can expect Bob to be around them at any time and any place.<ref name="Pop art on Saswata # TOI">{{cite news
|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-22/news-interviews/31224239_1_sujoy-ghosh-fan-frenzy-character
|title=Pop art on Saswata Chatterjee's character
|first=Roshni
|last=Mukherjee
|newspaper=The Times of India
|agency=TNN
|accessdate=11 June 2012
|date=22 March 2012
}}</ref>

Parambrata Chatterjee said in an interview that he did not identify with the Rana character, owing to the difference between his own urban upbringing and Rana's rural background.<ref name="param ready">{{cite news
|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/im-not-thinking-of-future-in-bollywood-parambrata-chatterjee/927457/0
|title=I'm not thinking of a future in Bollywood: Parambrata Chatterjee
|first= Namita
|last=Nivas
|newspaper=The Indian Express
|accessdate=26 March 2012
|date=23 March 2012
}}</ref> Chatterjee visited police stations and did some research "on their work, mindset and other relevant things" to prepare for the role.<ref name="param ready"/> The character Khan was envisaged as a ruthless, arrogant, expletive-spewing officer who cares nothing about the emotional or social consequences of his behaviour.<ref name="ghosh starananda interview khan">{{cite video
|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YtNMKGLGbCU
|title=Sujoy Ghosh, director of ''Kahaani'', exclusive interview with Star Ananda
|publisher=Star Ananda
|people=Ghosh, Sujoy
|type=Television production
|language=Bengali
|year=2012
|month= March
|time=8:15
|accessdate=30 March 2012
}}{{login required}}</ref> Siddiqui said that he was surprised on being offered the role, and wondered how he could portray the arrogance needed for the character.<ref name="siddiqui prep">{{cite news
|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/regional/news-interviews/Nawazuddin-Siddiqui-on-a-roll/articleshow/12273536.cms
|title=Nawazuddin Siddiqui on a roll
|first=Priyanka
|last=Dasgupta
|newspaper=The Times of India
|agency=TNN
|accessdate=26 March 2012
|date=15 March 2012
}}</ref> Ghosh built Khan as a character with lean physical build but full of mental strength, loyalty and patriotism. Khan smokes a relatively cheap brand of cigarette ([[Gold Flake]]) despite his high official post; Siddiqui had smoked that brand of cigarette throughout his struggling days in Bollywood and thereafter.<ref name="abp 7 april ghosh"/>

===Filming===
[[File:Sindur khela vermilion dashami durga puja bengali.jpg|thumb|The climax showed ''Sindoor khela'', a ritual on the last day of Durga Puja in which married women smear each other's face with ''sindoor'' (vermilion).| alt=One woman smearing the face of another with vermilion]]
Filming took place on the streets of Kolkata, where Ghosh often employed the art of [[guerrilla filmmaking]] (shooting in real locations without any previous knowledge given to onlookers) to avoid unwanted attention.<ref name="GhoshInterview">{{cite news
|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-11/news-interviews/31145194_1_kahaani-sujoy-ghosh-aladin
|title=Vidya Balan is a character driven actress: Sujoy Ghosh
|newspaper=The Times of India
|agency=TNN
|accessdate=11 March 2012
|date=15 March 2012
}}</ref><ref name>{{cite web
|url=http://businessofcinema.com/news/ghanchakkar-vidya-balan-takes-on-the-crowds-again/64019
|title=Ghanchakkar: Vidya Balan Takes On The Crowds<U+2026>Again
|publisher=Business of Cinema
|accessdate=14 June 2013
|date=6 March 2013
}}</ref> The cinematographer Setu, who had assisted others in the past to shoot documentaries in Kolkata, said that unlike majority of Indian films, ''Kahaani'' was shot mostly without artificial light.<ref name="setu iv">{{cite web|url= http://www.filmfare.com/interviews/kolkatas-night-rider-758.html| title=Kolkata's night rider | last=Sharma| first=Devesh|publisher=Filmfare|date=3 July 2012 | accessdate=26 May 2013}}</ref> The film was shot in 64 days,<ref name="Cakewalk @ ZN">{{cite news
|url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/movies/playing-pregnant-woman-was-cakewalk-for-vidya_103659.htm
|title=Playing pregnant woman was cakewalk for Vidya
|publisher=Zee News
|agency=IANS
|accessdate=21 May 2012
|date=11 January 2012
}}</ref> during which the [[Durga Puja]] festival of 2010 took place. Shooting locations in Kolkata included [[Kalighat]] Metro station, Nonapukur tram depot,{{efn|A [[Calcutta Tramways Company]] workshop on Bijli Road in Kolkata<ref>{{cite book|last=Nair|first=P. Thankappan|title=A history of Calcutta's streets|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=o40cAAAAMAAJ|year=1987|publisher=Firma KLM|page=216| oclc=18309970}}</ref>}} [[Kumartuli]], [[Howrah Bridge]], [[Victoria Memorial]], old houses of North Kolkata and others.<ref name="dasguptatoi152012"/><ref name="InExp2612">{{cite news|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/ami-shotti-bolchi-dedicated-to-kolkata-sujoy-ghosh/908494/|title=Vidya Balan's 'Ami Shotti Bolchi' dedicated to Kolkata|date=6 February 2012| accessdate=30 March 2013|newspaper=The Indian Express}}</ref> The climax, which takes place on the night of [[Vijayadashami]] (the last day of Durga Puja), was shot on the night of Vijayadashami in the premises of a ''[[Barowari]]'' (publicly organised) Durga Puja celebration in the [[Ballygunge]] neighbourhood of Kolkata. Most of the crowd in the climax were not actors. Some actors mingled with the crowd engaged in ''Sindoor khela''{{efn|''Sindoor khela'' is a ritual on Vijayadashami in which married women anoint each others' faces with ''sindoor'' (vermilion).<ref name="sindur book">{{cite book|last1=Foulston|first1=Lynn|last2=Abbott|first2=Stuart|
title=Hindu goddesses: beliefs and practices|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=XgwVgPx5G5UC|year=2009|
publisher=Sussex Academic Press|isbn=978-1-902210-43-8|page=167}}</ref><ref name="sindur dna">{{cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report_bidding-durga-goodbye-roll-up-your-sleeves-for-sindoor-khela_1755578|title=Bidding Durga goodbye: roll up your sleeves for Sindoor Khela|
last=Shukla| first= Ashutosh|
newspaper=DNA India|date=24 October 2012| accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref>}}<U+2014>their job was to appreciate the camera angles and accordingly apply ''[[sindoor]]'' (vermilion) on Balan's face so that accidental exposure of her eyes to ''sindoor'' could be avoided.<ref name="abp 7 april ghosh">{{cite web
|url=http://www.anandabazar.com/archive/1120407/7enter.html
|title='Kahaani'
|trans_title=Story
|first=Sujoy
|last=Ghosh
|work=[[Anandabazar Patrika]]
|language=Bengali
|accessdate=8 April 2012
|date=7 April 2012
}}</ref> 

Ghosh chose the guest house in which the protagonist stays after noticing it during his visit to a neighbouring hotel in April 2010. He booked it for 10 days for {{INRConvert|40|k}}, and requested the guest-house employees to keep the shooting schedule a secret. Choosing a room with windows overlooking a busy road, he proceeded to give it an old-fashioned look by replacing the windows' designer grilles with old-fashioned wooden ones, and by painting the room with some rough patches.<ref name="StarChamber" />

==Themes and influences==
After ''[[Ishqiya]]'' (2010), ''[[No One Killed Jessica]]'' (2011) and ''[[The Dirty Picture]]'' (2011), ''Kahaani'' was Balan's fourth [[women's film|woman-centric film]]<ref name=VidyaStrikeGold@ZN>{{cite news
|url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/movies/will-vidya-stike-gold-again-with-kahaani_107075.htm
|title=Will Vidya stike gold again with ''Kahaani''?
|publisher=Zee News
|agency=IANS
|accessdate=28 March 2012
|date=5 March 2012
}}</ref> to win widespread praise for her unconventional approach to portraying strong female roles.<ref name="Kahaani Rave Reviews">{{cite web
|url=http://entertainment.oneindia.in/bollywood/features/2012/kahaani-rave-reviews-critics-verdict-110312.html
|title=''Kahaani'' receives rave reviews from film critics
|publisher=OneIndia.in
|accessdate=11 March 2012
|date=11 March 2012
}}</ref><ref name=firstlook>{{cite news
|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Bollywood/FIRST-LOOK-Vidya-Balan-in-Kahaani/Article1-776399.aspx
|title=First look: Vidya Balan in ''Kahaani''
|newspaper=Hindustan Times
|accessdate=1 December 2011
|date=1 December 2011
}}</ref><ref>{{cite news
|url=http://archive.dailypioneer.com/component/content/article/346-show-time/48714-no-ordinary-kahaani.html
|title=No ordinary ''Kahaani''
|first=Meenakshi
|last=Rao
|newspaper=[[The Pioneer (Indian newspaper)|The Pioneer]]
|accessdate=6 April 2012
|date=10 March 2012
}}</ref> According to [[Zee News]], ''Kahaani'' is a woman's film about "role reversals, breaking of stereotypes, turning clich<U+00E9>s inside out, a woman's journey, and the way she carves a niche for herself in the male-dominated mentalscape of the society."<ref>{{cite web
|url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/movies/vidya-s-kahaani-has-a-male-heroine_107445.htm
|title=Vidya's ''Kahaani'' has a 'male' heroine!
|publisher=Zee News
|accessdate=21 March 2012
|date=12 March 2012
}}</ref> Trisha Gupta of ''[[The Indian Express]]'' also finds feminist themes in the film.<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/she-belongs-to-the-city/925371/0
|title=She belongs to the city
|first=Trisha
|last=Gupta
|newspaper=The Indian Express
|accessdate=30 March 2012
|date=19 March 2012
}}</ref> For Ghosh, one aspect of his project "is a study of motherhood"; the instinct of a mother to protect her baby inspired him to develop the story.<ref name=Sujoy@Rediff>{{cite web
|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-sujoy-ghosh-vidya-balan-is-the-hero-of-my-film/20120306.htm
|title=There are two heroes in ''Kahaani'': Vidya Balan and Kolkata
|first=Ankur
|last=Pathak
|publisher=Rediff
|accessdate=16 March 2012
|date=6 March 2012
}}</ref>

A recurring theme is the fleeting hint of romance between Rana and Vidya. Ghosh said that this delicate romance was "the most progressive thing" in the film<U+2014>a suggestion that a man could fall in love with a pregnant woman. The director explained that the boy was initially "fascinated by someone who is literally a hero in his eyes", as Rana was awed by the computer skills of Vidya. Gradually, the fascinated boy moves into a zone where he tries to protect her.<ref name="ibn ghosh interview romance">{{cite video
|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eaNZSI4zX2o&feature=related
|title=Rajeev Masand interview with director Sujoy Ghosh on ''Kahaani''
|publisher=CNN-IBN
|people=Ghosh, Sujoy
|type=Television production
|year=2012
|month=March
|time=2:07
|accessdate=30 March 2012
}}</ref>

[[File:Traffic in Kolkata.jpg|thumb|left|A road in Kolkata showing congested traffic and yellow taxis. The deft portrayal of the city in the film was noted by reviewers.|alt=A road in Kolkata showing congested traffic and yellow taxis]]

Some reviewers note that a major protagonist is Kolkata itself, which is "brimming with warm, sympathetic inhabitants".<ref name="rediff Review"/> A review in Rediff.com notes that the director pays a "fond yet understated tribute" to the city by incorporating imagery such as "yellow taxis, leisurely trams, congested traffic, claustrophobic metros, dilapidated brick houses, tapering alleys, rajnigandhas,{{efn|''Rajanigandha'' ([[tuberose]]) flowers are used in religious and social events in India.<ref>{{cite book|last=Singh|first=A. K.|title=Flower crops: cultivation and management|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=Bfb1T6QbfaAC&pg=PA4|date=1 January 2006|publisher=New India Publishing|isbn=978-81-89422-35-6|page=4}}</ref>}} lal paad saris,{{efn|''Lal paad sari'', meaning [[sari]] with red border, usually white sari with red border, is traditionally considered auspicious and worn in many religious or social occasions in [[Bengali culture]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Haque|first1=Enamul|last2=Bhattacharya|first2=Gouriswar|title=Kalh<U+0101>r (white water-lily): studies in art, iconography, architecture, and archaeology of India and Bangladesh|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=wcWfAAAAMAAJ|date=1 March 2007|publisher=Kaveri Books|isbn=978-81-7479-080-4|page=130}}</ref>}} piping hot luchis".{{efn|''[[Luchi]]'' is a deep-fried [[flatbread]] made of wheat flour, typical of [[Bengali cuisine|Bengali]] and some other cuisines. It is often eaten with a potato curry or a ''[[dal]]'' made of yellow split-peas.<ref>{{cite book|last=Banerji|first=Chitrita|title=Eating India: an Odyssey into the food and culture of the land of spices|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=XfjOQfPtmw0C&pg=PA71|date=10 December 2008|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing |isbn=978-1-59691-712-5|page=71}}</ref>}} According to the reviewer, ''Kahaani'' did not depend on the tropes of Kolkata culture typically used in Bollywood film<U+2014>"O-emphasizing accent, dramatic play of conch shells, [[rasgulla]]/[[mishti doi]] excesses."<ref name="rediff Review"/> The director acknowledges that Kolkata "becomes a central character" of the film.<ref name="dasguptatoi152012">{{cite news
|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/news-interviews/Kahaani-takes-Kolkata-beyond-cliches/articleshow/12273109.cms
|title=''Kahaani'' takes Kolkata beyond cliches
|first=Priyanka
|last=Dasgupta
|newspaper=The Times of India
|agency=TNN
|accessdate= 15 March 2012
|date=15 March 2012
}}</ref> Gautaman Bhaskaran, writing for ''[[Gulf Times]]'',<ref name="gautaman gt 14 March 2012"/> notes that Kolkata imagery was polished up in the film; noted Bengali director [[Srijit Mukherji]] argues that the portrayal of the city in ''Kahaani'' was akin to a "[[Lonely Planet]] exotica" on the city.<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-24/news-interviews/31233578_1_srijit-mukherji-films-shooting/3
|title=Hemlock is far from a morbid film: Srijit Mukherji
|first=Satadru
|last=Ojha
|newspaper=The Times of India
|accessdate=8 May 2012
|date=24 March 2012
}}</ref> Uddalak Mukherjee of ''The Telegraph'' explains that Kolkata in ''Kahaani'' was cosmetic and lacked a deep menacing presence.<ref name="mukherjee TT 4 December 2012"/> Mukherjee argues the depiction of the city never matches the level of [[Satyajit Ray]]'s [[Calcutta trilogy]], where "aided by bloodshed, greed and decadence,&nbsp;...Calcutta&nbsp;..., even though a place of dreams, desires and hope, slides irreversibly into chaos, anxiety and a moral crisis, taking its residents with it".<ref name="mukherjee TT 4 December 2012"/>

[[Durga Puja]], the autumnal festival to worship goddess [[Durga]], plays a prominent role in the story.<ref name="mukherjee TT 4 December 2012">{{cite news
|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1120412/jsp/opinion/story_15361368.jsp#.T6lsl9kqxJF
|title=A tale of two cities
|newspaper=The Telegraph
|first=Uddalak
|last=Mukherjee
|accessdate=8 May 2012
|date=12 April 2012
|location=Calcutta, India
}}</ref> The allegorical yearly return of goddess Durga to slay the demon [[Mahishasura]] is alluded to at the end of the film.<ref name="mukherjee TT 4 December 2012"/> According to Uddalak Mukherjee of ''The Telegraph'', "Durga Puja, with its paraphernalia of idols, immersion processions, ''[[pandals]]'', even an entire crowd of women draped in white ''saris'' with red borders, is central to the film's&nbsp;... visual aesthetic."<ref name="mukherjee TT 4 December 2012"/> A review in Rediff.com praised the depiction of the festivities in Kolkata, a city well known for its celebration of Durga Puja.<ref name="rediff Review"/>

[[File:Pratima Visarjan by Gaganendranath Tagore.png|thumb|The colour scheme of ''Kahaani'' was inspired by the painting ''Pratima Visarjan'' by [[Gaganendranath Tagore]].|alt=A painting by Gaganendranath Tagore depicting the color inspiration of the film]]

Ghosh acknowledges the allusions to Ray's films. In one scene, Vidya asks the manager of the guest house why there is no hot water although the signboard had claimed "running hot water". The manager explains that the sign refers for his errand boy, who runs to deliver hot water in a kettle whenever required. This alludes to a similar scene in Ray's ''[[Joy Baba Felunath]]'' (1979).<ref name="anandabazreview">{{cite web
|url=http://www.anandabazar.com/archive/1120317/17cine1.html
|title='Asamanya'
|trans_title=Extraordinary
|first=Jagari
|last=Bandyopadhyay
|work=Anandabazar Patrika
|language=Bengali
|accessdate=18 March 2012
|date=17 March 2012
}}</ref> In an interview with ''The Telegraph'', Ghosh says that the way Balan looks out and moves from window to window in the guest-house room is reminiscent of Ray's ''[[Charulata]]'' (1964), where the actress [[Madhabi Mukherjee]] enjoys glimpses of the outside world through the blinds of windows. He also acknowledges the influence of ''[[Mahanagar]]'' (1963), another Ray film noted for its portrayal of Kolkata. According to the director, he was inspired by particular scenes of Ray's ''[[Nayak (1966 film)|Nayak]]'' (1966) to plan the portrayal of complex emotional issues between Vidya and the police officer Rana, especially Rana's awe in the presence of Vidya. Ghosh expresses his inspiration from Ray's ''[[Aranyer Dinratri]]'' (1970) in which Ray "wanted the audience to be inside the car with the four guys all the time. So the camera never leaves the car." Ghosh shot a similar scene, hoping the audience would become "like Vidya's fellow passenger."<ref name="gupta ghosh interview tt">{{cite news
|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1120314/jsp/entertainment/story_15245793.jsp
|title=Salaam namaste
|first=Pratim D.
|last=Gupta
|newspaper=The Telegraph
|accessdate=18 March 2012
|date=14 March 2012
|location=Calcutta, India
}}</ref>

Besides Ray's films, Ghosh also admits inspiration from what he calls "visually striking" films of 1970s and 1980s, such as ''[[Deewaar (1975 film)|Deewaar]]'' (1975).<ref name="gupta ghosh interview tt"/> Critics have compared the fake-pregnancy twist of ''Kahaani'' with the 2004 American psychological thriller ''[[Taking Lives (film)|Taking Lives]]''.<ref name="anandabazreview"/> The sequences towards the end that explain the missing pieces of the mystery were compared with ''[[The Usual Suspects]]'' (1995).<ref name="choprahindustan"/> Ghosh writes that the film was heavily influenced by the colour scheme of the ''Pratima Visarjan'', a c.1915 watercolour by the [[Bengal School of Art|Bengal School]] artist [[Gaganendranath Tagore]].<ref name="abp 7 april ghosh"/>

==Soundtrack==
{{Infobox album
